{
    "SKILLS_EXTRACTION_PROMPT": "Extract specific technical skills, tools, software, and hard competencies from this job description. Focus on concrete items that would typically appear in a 'Technical Skills' or 'Tools' section of a resume.\n\nCATEGORIES TO INCLUDE:\n- Software & Tools (e.g., Salesforce, Excel, Photoshop, SAP, Jira)\n- Programming & Scripting (e.g., Python, SQL, Java, VBA)\n- Frameworks & Libraries (e.g., React, Spring, .NET, Pandas)\n- Cloud & Infrastructure (e.g., AWS, Azure, Docker, Kubernetes)\n- Industry Standards & Methodologies (e.g., IFRS, Agile, ISO 9001, Six Sigma)\n- Regulatory/Legal Standards (e.g., GDPR, HIPAA, SOC2)\n- Languages (e.g., Fluent English, German B2)\n\nDO NOT EXTRACT:\n- Soft skills (e.g., communication, leadership, team player, motivated)\n- Vague responsibilities (e.g., project management, data analysis, reporting)\n- Common workplace concepts (e.g., remote work, flexible hours, meetings)\n\nNORMALIZATION RULES:\n- Use industry-standard acronyms (e.g., 'Search Engine Optimization' -> 'SEO')\n- Translate local-language technical terms to their English standard equivalent if applicable.\n- Keep version numbers only if they are highly specific to the role.\n\nJob Description:\n\"\"\"\n{description}\n\"\"\"\n\nReturn ONLY a JSON object: {{\"skills\": [\"Skill 1\", \"Skill 2\", ...]}}",
    "SKILLS_MATCHING_PROMPT": "Categorize each job skill as 'matched', 'partial', or 'missing' based on the candidate's profile.\n\nLOGIC:\n- matched: The candidate explicitly has this skill or an exact synonym.\n- partial: The candidate has a different skill within the same specific functional category that would significantly reduce the learning curve (e.g., different software in the same suite, or a similar methodology).\n- missing: The candidate lacks the skill and has no closely related experience.\n\nCANDIDATE PROFILE:\n{candidate_skills}\n\nREQUIRED JOB SKILLS:\n{job_skills}\n\nCategorize every required job skill into one of the three categories provided.",
    "JOB_SCORING_PROMPT": "You are a strict recruitment AI. Evaluate the match between the candidate and the job. Be harsh regarding seniority and mandatory requirements.\n\nCRITICAL DISQUALIFIERS (Max Score: 2/10):\n- Status Mismatch: If the job is an **Internship/Thesis/Student Job** and the candidate is a working professional (already graduated).\n- Seniority Mismatch: If the job is **Senior/Lead/Principal** (requiring 5+ years experience) and the candidate is Junior/Mid (has <3 years experience).\n- Language Barrier: If the job requires a specific language at Native/Fluent level that the candidate only speaks at Intermediate/Basic level.\n- Domain Mismatch: If the job requires a specific degree (e.g., Medical, Law) that the candidate does not have.\n\nSCORING SCALE:\n- 0-2: Disqualified (See above).\n- 3-5: Tech stack matches, but industry/domain is wrong, or experience is slightly too low.\n- 6-8: Good match. Meets seniority and most technical skills.\n- 9-10: Perfect match. Meets all requirements + nice-to-haves.\n\nCANDIDATE RESUME:\n{resume}\n\nJOB DESCRIPTION:\nTitle: {title}\nCompany: {company}\nDescription:\n{description}\n\nOUTPUT FORMAT:\nSCORE: [Number]\nREASONING: [Explain the score. If low, explicitly state the disqualifier (e.g., 'Seniority gap', 'Internship mismatch').]",
    "JOB_SCORING_SYSTEM_PROMPT": "You are a professional recruitment auditor. Your role is to determine if a candidate is a viable contender for a role.",
    "resume_tailoring": "You are tailoring a candidate's LaTeX resume to a specific job.\n\nYou are given three things:\n1. INFORMATION BANK: a plain-text record of ALL the candidate's experience, projects, and\n   skills. It is a superset and contains more than fits on a one-page resume. You may draw\n   relevant details from here to add to the resume.\n2. CURRENT RESUME: the LaTeX body of the resume as it stands. This is the file you edit.\n3. JOB: the target job description.\n\nProduce edits that re-emphasize, rephrase, and reorder the resume to better match the JOB, and\nthat pull in relevant experience or projects from the INFORMATION BANK where they fit the job\nbetter than what is currently shown.\n\nOutput ONLY a JSON object of the form {{\"edits\": [...]}}, with no prose and no markdown fences.\nEach element: {{\"search\": \"...\", \"replacement\": \"...\", \"reason\": \"...\"}}.\n\nRules:\n- \"search\" MUST be a verbatim substring of the CURRENT RESUME (the LaTeX). Never take \"search\"\n  from the INFORMATION BANK.\n- \"replacement\" is the new LaTeX that replaces \"search\". It may incorporate facts drawn from the\n  INFORMATION BANK.\n- If the resume contains tokens like [[REDACT_1]], treat them as opaque identifiers. Reproduce every [[REDACT_N]] token VERBATIM in any \"replacement\" where it appears; never alter, split, translate, escape, or otherwise transform these tokens.\n- Only edit content (summary, experience bullets, the skills line). NEVER touch LaTeX preamble,\n  custom commands, or document structure.\n- NEVER fabricate. Every claim in \"replacement\" must be supported by the INFORMATION BANK or the\n  CURRENT RESUME. Do not invent employers, titles, dates, or metrics.\n- Do not add content that substantially repeats an existing bullet. To strengthen existing\n  experience, edit that bullet in place rather than adding a near-duplicate.\n- Resume space is limited to one page. Prefer rewriting or replacing existing content over adding\n  new lines. Only add a new bullet when it introduces materially new, job-relevant information.\n- Keep the LaTeX valid: preserve surrounding commands and escape special characters\n  (& % $ # _) in any added prose.\n- \"reason\" briefly ties the edit to the JOB.\n\nINFORMATION BANK:\n\"\"\"\n{information_bank}\n\"\"\"\n\nCURRENT RESUME:\n\"\"\"\n{current_resume}\n\"\"\"\n\nJOB:\nTitle: {title}\nCompany: {company}\nLocation: {location}\nDescription:\n{description}"
}